    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-18T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-18T09:00:00-05:00" n="818"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d818">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112 European War 1939/331: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Denmark</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-18T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 18, 1939—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 18—11:33 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>105. Would urgently appreciate substance of any recent discussions Department has
                    had with Danish or other Nordic Ministers regarding “neutral trade” (more
                    especially as it may relate to contraband) since Foreign Office advises me
                    Foreign Secretary hopes to discuss this question with me on his return from
                    Stockholm.</p>
                <p>In possible explanation of above I learn from Foreign Office source that just
                    before Stockholm conference German Legations have made representations
                    Copenhagen, Oslo and presumably Stockholm referring with some satisfaction to
                    alleged “contraband resolution” of Pan-American Conference regarding
                    non-inclusion of supplies for civilian population.</p>
                <p>I have no knowledge of any such resolution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
